"The greatness of a nation and its moral progress can be judged by the way its animals are treated." Mahatma Gandhi
When I think of my grandma, I see her sitting in her rocking chair in the middle of her backyard. It’s summertime, and I’m swinging on a tree branch, listening to the melodious songs of birds. In the meantime, she’s knitting something warm and cozy for the upcoming winter. As she’s knitting, she talks to me about my day, about her day, about our day. We talk about how I have to do better in school, how she has to do better in her life, and how we have to do better in the world. We are one. We are a family. We are a home. We are love. We are all. My grandma is my hero. She is the reason I am here today. When I was in the fourth grade, I didn’t want to go to school. I hated my teachers, I hated my friends, and I hated school in general. I had never gotten any lower than a B in school, and I never got anything lower than a C. However, my teachers gave me a C- on my math test. I was so frustrated that I cried for an hour. I didn’t understand how I could get a C- in math. It just didn’t make any sense. I was so mad that I went to my room and didn’t want to do anything. I didn’t want to eat, I didn’t want to sleep, and I didn’t want to play. My mom and dad were worried about me, so they decided to go to a family counselor. The family counselor told my parents that they needed to take me to see my grandma. They said that I had been spending too much time with my grandma and that I needed to
